### 🐛 Current behavior

connectSortBy is file node_modules/instantsearch.js/es/connectors/sort-by/connectSortBy.js

```javascript
getWidgetUiState: function getWidgetUiState(uiState, _ref4) {
        var searchParameters = _ref4.searchParameters;
        var currentIndex = searchParameters.index;
        return _objectSpread(_objectSpread({}, uiState), {}, {
          sortBy: currentIndex !== connectorState.initialIndex ? currentIndex : undefined
        });
      },
```

The code above doesn't make sense on the face of it. Why are we changing this to undefined when the currentIndex is the initial index? 

### 🔍 Steps to reproduce

See below. 

### Live reproduction

No sandbox should be necessary.

### 💭 Expected behavior

In my stateMapper's routetoState function, if I set an index sortBy to that index I should expect to sort on that index and not get a series of reloads and redirects, but the code above causes exactly this.  The correct code seems to be 

```javascript
return _objectSpread(_objectSpread({}, uiState), {}, {
          sortBy: currentIndex ?? connectorState.initialIndex
        });
```
This insures we have a value for sortBy if a sortBy value was provided.

If this isn't the case and the code is fine as is, then the documentation for building a custom stateMapper needs to be made far more clear as to what the initial value of the sortBy parameter should be when the default sort is to be used.

### Package version

instantsearch 4.75.4

### Operating system

OSX Sequoia

### Browser

Edge Latest

